'''Netsu Motonao''' (禰津元直) was a {{ill|samurai|ja|侍|qq=draft}} of the {{ill|Sengoku period (Japan)|ja|戦国時代 (日本)|qq=draft}}, known for his service to the {{ill|Takeda clan|ja|武田氏|qq=draft}}. His family name is also written as Nezu or Nesu.
== Overview == The {{ill|Netsu clan|ja|禰津氏|qq=draft}} was a {{ill|kokujin|ja|国人|qq=draft}} clan based in {{ill|Netsu, Chiisagata District, Shinano Province|ja|信濃国小県郡禰津|qq=draft}} (modern-day {{ill|Tōmi, Nagano|ja|長野県東御市|qq=draft}}).<ref name="maru561"/>
In {{ill|Tenbun|ja|天文|qq=draft}} 10 (1541), during {{ill|Takeda Nobutora|ja|武田信虎|qq=draft}}'s invasion of Chiisagata (the {{ill|Battle of Uedahara|ja|海野平の戦い|qq=draft}}), the Netsu clan was defeated. However, through mediation by {{ill|Suwa Yorishige|ja|諏訪頼重|qq=draft}}, a fellow member of the Suwa Shrine priestly lineage, Motonao submitted to the Takeda clan. He was placed under the supervision of {{ill|Takeda Nobukado|ja|武田信廉|qq=draft}} and retained his lands.<ref name="maru561"/>
According to the ''{{ill|Takahakasaiki|ja|高白斎記|qq=draft}},'' on the 15th day of the 12th month in Tenbun 11 (1542), one of Motonao's daughters married {{ill|Takeda Harunobu|ja|武田晴信|qq=draft}} (later Takeda Shingen) as a concubine. She was known as {{ill|Netsu Goryōnin|ja|禰津御寮人|qq=draft}}.<ref name="maru561"/> The ''Takahakasaiki'' mentions a "person from Netsu" entering the Takeda household, a description traditionally attributed to Netsu Goryōnin. However, some scholars argue this might refer to {{ill|Suwa Goryōnin|ja|諏訪御料人|qq=draft}}, a daughter of Suwa Yorishige.
In Tenbun 22 (1553), Motonao was granted an estate worth 1,000 ''kanmon'' in the Shōnai area (modern-day {{ill|Sakaki, Nagano|ja|長野県坂城町|qq=draft}}).<ref name="maru561"/> Among his children, {{ill|Netsu Katsunao|ja|禰津勝直|qq=draft}} predeceased him, so the family leadership passed to his second son, {{ill|Netsu Masanao|ja|禰津政直|qq=draft}} (also known as Masahide or by his monastic name, Matsōken Jōan).<ref name="maru561"/>
== References == <references />
== Further Reading == * Marushima Kazuhiro, "Netsu Motonao," in {{ill|Takeda Clan Retainers Biographical Dictionary|ja|武田氏家臣団人名辞典|qq=draft}}, edited by Shibazuki Toshinobu, Hirayama Masaru, Kuroda Motoki, and Marushima Kazuhiro, Tōkyōdō Shuppan, 2015. * Tanaka Toyoshige, ''Shinano Chūsei Buke-den,'' Shinano Mainichi Shimbunsha, 2016.
